On 18/05/2009, David Saff &lt;david@...&gt; wrote:
&gt; To be clear, my proposal was a single syntax that would allow
&gt; hamcrest-style assertions from a boolean method on any non-final
&gt; class, including:
&gt;
&gt; assertThat(list).isEmpty();
&gt; assertThat(list).equals(list2);
&gt; assertThat(list).contains(item);
&gt; assertThat(file).exists();
&gt; assertThat(objectStreamField).isPrimitive();
&gt;
&gt; The _big_ blocker for this idea is that String is final, meaning that
&gt; there&#39;s no way to use the same syntax to get this to compile:
&gt;
&gt; assertThat(&quot;abc&quot;).contains(&quot;c&quot;);

You could write a special-case overload for Strings that returned some
kind of string-matcher-builder. It&#39;s a kludge but maybe consistency
would be worth it.

Also, what about accessors that return types other than boolean? I&#39;m
sure there&#39;s a way to automagically generate composite matchers for
them somehow.

By the way, there is at least one project on google-code that does
half of this: generate matchers using reflection and cglib.

